Completing I-9 Sections 1 & 2

Good Morning, 
I wanted to reach out about my 8AM exam this morning that is to be rescheduled for 
Wednesday. The 2PM option works for me. 
Secondly, I'd like to point out the following: 
I understand there is nothing that could really be done, and my exam was likely going to 
be rescheduled regardless. But I think it was highly inconsiderate how it was handled. I 
know the office received notice from my professor before 8 AM this morning that my 
exam was not to be taken today; because when I arrived prior to 8AM, I was informed 
that my professor did not want me taking it today. As a DISABILITY resource office, I 
would like to think the office would understand the potential harm to one of their 
registered students for not informing them ASAP. Even if the office did not know until 
the first person arrived this morning, an email would have been much better. To give 
you a sense this is where I stand now: 
I am a student with ADHD, I took my meds at 6AM so that they could be in effect by 
8AM. This means, they will no longer be working around 6-7 PM this evening. I have an 
exam today at 3:30, so my priority from getting home this morning to 3:30 will be 
studying for that exam. When I get home around 4:30 or 5, I will have approximately an 
hour of study time (as my meds will not be working past 6). I have two exams the next 
day at 8AM and 2PM, so my focus will be my 8AM exam, leaving me with no prep for 
my 2PM exam. Then, I get home another day at 5:45, after a day of taking my meds at 
6AM and will barely be able to study for my NOW Wednesday exam at 2PM. So now, I 
have almost 2 days to lose all knowledge for my exam. Of course this is a bit of an 
exaggeration, and since I have lived with ADHD for almost 21 years, I have 
mechanisms to try and study after my meds are worn off, but I still am not as 
productive.  
I know there was not much you could do, but I want to bring attention to how highly 
inconsiderate it was to not inform me immediately after knowing the situation. And how 
ESPECIALLY inconsiderate it was to send me my location notice at 5:19 PM if you guys 
had already known (which I suspect/hope you did not). I do appreciate your time and 
effort to reschedule my exam. I just wanted to let you know so that maybe if this 
happens to another/with another student in the future it can be prevented. 
Thank you for your time, 
Chloe Coursey

Hi Chloe, For Assignment 3A, I am not asking you to make up any background 
experience. Your ethos will simply be based on the correctness and professionalism of the 
overall formal proposal.
I am sending the following information each of your team members in response to this online 
activity:
Be sure to read all of the notes about each section that is required for Assignment 3A – 
Collaborative Instruction Proposal. The notes for the proposal body include information about 
writing step-by-step instructions. The following “must have” list should help you get started on 
writing instructions if you have not already started:
Introduction and informative title – Tell the user in one line, and in more detail what he/she 
will be accomplishing by using the instructions. Include all materials that are needed, as well as 
time required.
Step-by-step list – Use numbered lists with each step beginning with a very specific action verb 
followed by a description of the expected reaction or result, or a common problem that may 
occur if the action is done incorrectly
Format, fonts, and figures – Use an easy to follow format with varying fonts to give the users 
cues about what the information provides (e.g., bold for all actions, a different font for 
cautions, warning, and dangers, etc.). Use visuals with proper labels to illustrate complex steps, 
or ones that require an important outcome.
Cautions, Warnings, and Danger Notices – Use the legally correct level of warning. A lot of 
instructions do not meet that standard for what could happen if an action is taken by a user 
(e.g., Cautions are used if a wrong result can occur; Warnings are used if something can be 
broken; Dangers are used if physical harm can result.). Also, include appropriate warning 
notices in the steps where they apply.
Conclusion – Provide information that recaps what the final result should be, as well as 
information for additional information or support.
Take a moment to look at a quick some notes about Professional and Writing/Instructions, 
which have some good tips about instruction writing, as well as usability testing 
- https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Professional_and_Technical_Writing/Instructions 
Have a great day.
Jamie

Sent: Saturday, May 4, 2024 12:46 PM 
To: Victoria Cetrone <vcetrone@olgchs.org> 
Subject: Hayden Coursey test 
Hello Ms. Cetrone, 
  
Please do not tell Hayden that I sent you this email. He doesn't like us contacting his 
teachers, and while we encourage him to be independent in this regard, his anxiety 
does still occasionally hold him back from reaching out to teachers in some situations. 
Nevertheless, it is our responsibility to ensure his anxiety and ADHD are under the best 
control possible and that he is utilizing all available tools. 
  
We all understand that the responsibility for this situation lies entirely with Hayden. My 
goal is simply to figure out what options are available to him so I can provide him with 
as many tools as possible to avoid it in the future. 
  
The problem is that Hayden did not realize there was going to be a History test 
yesterday (hence his poor grade). I asked how he was expected to know about the test. 
He said it was posted in the Google Classroom stream but he keeps forgetting to read 
that - instead he goes directly to his "to do" list and all assignments are posted there. 
We discussed the importance of reading the stream each day, because even if it is 
mostly the same information as the to do list, even one piece of critical information (like 
the announcement of the test), makes it worth reading daily.  
  
His not reading the stream and going straight to the "to do" list is partly a function of his 
anxiety. Though it is under pretty good control thanks to medication and years of 
cognitive-behavioral therapy, it does still manifest in certain scenarios, one of which is 
his getting his homework done. While he no longer races through homework, he does 
race to get started on it, and has a major anxiety spike if faced with any delay prior to 
starting. This definitely plays a role in him skipping the feed and going straight to the "to 
do" list.  
 
I’m not making excuses for him; I just want you to understand in case you have any 
helpful ideas. My question to you is whether there was any other way Hayden should 
have known about the test. Did he miss an announcement in class? Was it posted 
elsewhere that he should have seen? 
  
We did discuss how he could better utilize his planner to help him remember to check 
the stream. If the answer is simply that he needs to be better about checking the stream 
then I think we have done all we can for the time being. I am hopeful that this situation 
will reinforce the importance of checking all sources daily for critical information. 
  
As always, any additional thoughts or ideas you have are very much welcomed. Thank 
you for reading such a lengthy email. 
  
Megan Coursey
